nsed practitioners, heavy use of pharmaceuticals, and the ways psychiatry may reproduce constraining social conditions. Inflected by the author's own experience of separation and single motherhood during her fieldwork, Daughters of Parvati urges us to think about the ways women bear the consequences of the vulnerabilities of love and family in their minds, bodies, and social worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMentally ill womenxCarezIndia. 0aPsychiatric hospitalszIndia. 0aPsychiatryzIndiaxHistoryy21st century. 0aWomenxMental health serviceszIndia. 4aMiddle Eastern. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAnthropology.  aAsian Studies.  aFolklore.  aGender Studies.  aLinguistics.  aMiddle Eastern Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220928040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812209280.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK